# Flink agent instructions

You are looking at a Flink server. Flink is a simple application server built for agents to publish prototype apps and single-page apps as live static websites with built-in browser APIs for JSON storage, uploads, realtime rooms, and optional AI calls.

If a user asks you to publish or deploy a prototype app to this server, do the work yourself with the Flink CLI. Do not ask the user to clone this repository, build Flink, choose infrastructure, or set up a separate backend.
{{if not .DomainHosting}}

This Flink server does not have domain-based hosting configured, so use path-based tenant URLs.
{{end}}

Inputs you need:

- FLINK_SERVER: {{.Server}}
- FLINK_TENANT: the tenant username
- FLINK_PASSWORD: the tenant password
- site name: a lowercase slug such as my-site
- files to publish: usually ./dist for a built app, or ./index.html for a single-file prototype

Use this exact URL pattern for published websites:
{{.SiteURLPattern}}
{{if .DomainHosting}}

For example, tenant demo and site my-site will be available at:

https://demo--my-site.{{.BaseHost}}/
{{end}}

Download the Flink CLI from GitHub Releases. Do not ask the user to clone the repository or build the CLI from source.

- Linux amd64: {{.CLIBase}}flink_linux_amd64.tar.gz
- Linux arm64: {{.CLIBase}}flink_linux_arm64.tar.gz
- macOS amd64: {{.CLIBase}}flink_darwin_amd64.tar.gz
- macOS arm64: {{.CLIBase}}flink_darwin_arm64.tar.gz

Install and configure the CLI:

curl -L -o flink.tar.gz {{.CLIBase}}flink_linux_amd64.tar.gz
tar -xzf flink.tar.gz

export FLINK_SERVER={{.Server}}
export FLINK_TENANT=<tenant>
export FLINK_PASSWORD=<password>

Use a Flink template early when starting from scratch. Templates create a usable static prototype with the browser SDK already wired in, which is faster and safer than beginning from an empty file:

./flink init todo ./my-site --site my-site

Deployment flow:

1. Build the app into static files if it has a build step.
2. If starting from scratch, create a template with `flink init <template>`.
3. Publish either the build directory or the single HTML file with `flink publish`.
4. Change site access with `flink auth` if the user wants to share it.
5. Use the URL printed by the CLI to verify the app.

Publish a built app or static directory:

./flink publish ./dist --site my-site

Publish a single-page HTML prototype:

./flink publish ./index.html --site my-site

Site access uses this server's default site auth mode when created. To make a site visible without signing in, run:

./flink auth my-site none

To require any approved tenant login, run:

./flink auth my-site tenants

To restrict to specific tenants, run:

./flink auth my-site tenants <tenant>...

For multi-file websites, publish a directory. Paths are preserved under the same {{if .DomainHosting}}domain{{else}}site base{{end}}:

- ./dist/index.html -> {{.IndexURL}}
- ./dist/assets/app.css -> {{.AssetURL}}
- ./dist/docs/index.html -> {{.DocsURL}}

Hosted sites can use Flink backend APIs by importing:

<script src="/flink.js"></script>

Use Flink storage, uploads, realtime rooms, and AI from browser code instead of creating a custom backend. Keep the first deployed version usable, then iterate by running `./flink publish` again for the same site.
